changes in class balance kicked in, and now have a confortable advance in realm abilties, equipment and player skill/tactics over the average opponent in the frontier (well some of the vocal ones at least, many others veterans are truly appealed by the fall of the once-all powerful class).<br>
<br>
However, for the majority of RvR-able skalds, your average level 50 RR 2-5 looking for group in the frontier keep, the morale is pretty low, that's for sure. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vivaxkithicor>Vivax Kithicor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Member</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/16/03 10:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=453.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well</span><hr size=1> I've been level 50 for about a calendar year,<br>
and at rank 5 level 7 (with no duelling to inflate my realm points) I've learned a bit of RvR.  I'm only R5L7 because I took 9/02-12/02 afk.<br>
<br>
But there *IS* a silver lining about being a 50 skald:  RvR groups beg for you to join them!<br>
<br>
(As ironic as it sounds, on Guinevere it's common to see level 50 healers LFG for RvR.  That's a wild change from the past Summer.)<br>
<br>
But back to the point, I wish the Dragon would drop a &quot;change class&quot; stone.  I'd change.<br>
<br>
